          <section id="structure-and-semantics" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#structure-and-semantics">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Structure and Semantics</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>Researchers exchange units of communication like scientific literature, annotation, datasets, workflows, argumentation, provenance, citation, and software. Knowledge may be represented or presented dynamically, or as a compilation of various independent units (compound). Semantic structure may be embedded in narrative or prose-based scholarly communication as well as used to enhance non-narrative units like experimental results or datasets. Narrative and non-narrative units may in turn include or refer to each other.</p>

              <p>This section covers semantic structure of the narrative aspects scholarly communication in particular. This can enhance <em>both</em> human- and machine-readability of information. Note also that we are interested here in structured representations of units irrespective of how they are produced.</p>

              <p>Non-narrative units can also be semantically marked up to enable easier reuse and interpretation; this is covered in more detail in <cite><a href="interactive-linked-statistics">Interactive Linked Statistics</a></cite>.</p> 


              <p class="todo">Discuss whether it is only about the "document"/container or if it incorporates the graph around it</p>

              <p cass="todo"><cite><a href="https://linkedsoftwaredependencies.org/articles/reproducibility/">Components.js: a semantic dependency injection framework for addressable and discoverable software configurations</a></cite>... for high level objects... there is a netowrk of htings and direction of links... their discoverability</p>

